<h3 id="wimbley-wombley-timey-wimey-stuff">Wimbley-Wombley, Timey-Wimey Stuff</h3>

<p>Time is just like, a construct, man. Itâ€™s all in your mind. This is something Iâ€™ve found is important to remember when setting goals. I wanted to run 5:00/km by the end of 2019 and I didnâ€™t hit that target, butâ€¦ so what? Really, the â€œtimelyâ€ part of setting goals is more about having an approximate expiration date on it. Goals are like canned soup - the expiration date is more of a suggestion anyway. (Legal disclaimer: I just ate soup that was two years out of date and Iâ€™m fine, so you probably should too.) If you donâ€™t make it, thatâ€™s okay! Just set a new timely goal, and work towards that.</p>

<p>On the other hand, donâ€™t be too loose with your time constraints. I think this is one reason why new yearâ€™s resolutions so often fail - because doing something â€œthis yearâ€ is just reallyâ€¦ nebulous. Smaller, shorter-term goals are going to be easier to track and stick to than larger, longer-term ones. â€œRun a &lt;5:00/km 5kâ€ is something I can set my sights on in a few weeks or months - â€œrun a marathonâ€ is a significantly larger timescale, and I donâ€™t really have any checkpoints along the way to know how Iâ€™m doing. Think of this as thin-slicing your work - by having smaller, shorter-term goals, you can constantly be checking up and checking in on whatâ€™s working, what isnâ€™t, what needs to be adjusted, etc.</p>

<p>In summary, set time limits. Then ignore them.</p>

